{
  "text": "The primary goal of this study is to develop for engineering applications an attenuation relationship for strong-motion data that have a certain distance and intensity threshold. However, it is worth mentioning that our versatile approach can also be easily applied for distant data (historically of interest in regional seismology). For a number of recent earthquakes, researchers have made an effort to combine classical strong-motion data sets (with triggered instruments) with data from seismological stations with continuous registration (e.g., [CITATION_1] . Data from California earthquakes (e.g., Parkfield and San Simeon) recorded at distant stations with amplitudes of ground acceleration less than 0.005 g (typical triggering level of strong-motion instruments) demonstrate much faster attenuation with significant change of slope at large distances of more than 150-200 km from fault rupture (Figure 17 ). Much faster attenuation of PGA (of the order of R \u22123 ) at large distances still requires physical interpretation. Nevertheless, the approach presented herein (through connecting a series of filters) is capable of capturing this long-distance fast-attenuation phenomenon by implementing another distance-dependent filter. Figure 17 demonstrate the predictive power of the attenuation curve with an additional filter against the long-distance PGA data retrieved during the Parkfield earthquake.",
